  1. Make a plot that shows the number of items ordered in each aisle, limiting this to aisles with more than 10000 items ordered. Arrange aisles sensibly, and organize your plot so others can read it.
instacart %>% 
  count (aisle) %>% 
  filter (n>10000) %>% 
  mutate(
    aisle = factor(aisle),
    aisle = fct_reorder(aisle, n)
  ) %>% 
  ggplot (aes(x = aisle, y = n)) + geom_point() + theme(axis.text = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1))

  1. Make a table showing the three most popular items in each of the aisles baking ingredients, dog food care, and packaged vegetables fruits. Include the number of times each item is ordered in your table.
instacart %>%

Your final dataset should include all originally observed variables and values; have useful variable names; include a weekday vs weekend variable; and encode data with reasonable variable classes. accel_df = read_csv("./data/accel_data.csv") %>% 
janitor::clean_names() %>% 

pivot_longer(activity_1:activity_1440,
             names_to = "min_of_day",
             names_prefix = "activity_",
             values_to = "activity_count") %>% 
  
  mutate(
         day=as.factor(day),
         activity_count=as.numeric(activity_count),
  min_of_day=as.numeric(min_of_day),
  day_id=as.numeric(day_id),
  week=as.numeric(week)
  ) %>% 
  
  
  mutate(weekdays_vs_weekend = case_when(
           day  %in% c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday") ~ "Weekdays",
          day  %in% c("Saturday", "Sunday") ~ "Weekend")) %>% 

  select(week, weekdays_vs_weekend, day_id, day_of_wk=day,everything())

  1. Traditional analyses of accelerometer data focus on the total activity over the day. Using your tidied dataset, aggregate accross minutes to create a total activity variable for each day, and create a table showing these totals. Are any trends apparent?
accel_df %>%  
  mutate(
         day_of_wk=as.factor(day_of_wk),
         activity_count=as.numeric(activity_count),
  min_of_day=as.numeric(min_of_day),
  day_id=as.numeric(day_id),
  week=as.numeric(week)
  ) %>% 
   mutate(day_of_wk = forcats::fct_relevel(day_of_wk, c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"))) %>% 
    
  group_by(week, day_of_wk, weekdays_vs_weekend) %>%
  summarise(total_daily_activity = sum(activity_count)) %>%

  knitr::kable()

  1. Accelerometer data allows the inspection activity over the course of the day. Make a single-panel plot that shows the 24-hour activity time courses for each day and use color to indicate day of the week. Describe in words any patterns or conclusions you can make based on this graph.
accel_df %>%   
  ggplot(aes(x = min_of_day, y = activity_count, color = day_of_wk)) + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) + 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  labs(
    title = "Activity in the day ",
    caption = "Accelerometer Data collected on a 63 year-old male with BMI 25, who was admitted to the Advanced Cardiac Care Center of Columbia University Medical Center and diagnosed with congestive heart failure (CHF), during a five weeks of observation period. "
  )
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

From the plot we can notice that the male study object has more activities at noon and night during each day of the week, especially on the Friday and Sunday. During weekdays the activity counts are more stable throughout the day. Activity counts are lower during the Saturdays of each week.

###Problem 3 1. load dataset.Do some data cleaning. Create separate variables for year, month, and day. Ensure observations for temperature, precipitation, and snowfall are given in reasonable units. For snowfall, what are the most commonly observed values? Why?

data("ny_noaa")
nycweather_df = 
  ny_noaa %>%
  mutate(
    ny_noaa,
    prcp = prcp/10,
    tmax = as.numeric(tmax)/10,
    tmin = as.numeric(tmin)/10
  ) %>%
  janitor::clean_names() %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  separate(date, c("year", "month", "day")) %>% 
  mutate(
    year = as.integer(year),
    month = month.name[as.integer(month)],
    day = as.integer(day)
    )

This dataset collects the data of weather conditions from all monitoning stations in NY, during January 1, 1981 through December 31, 2010. It contains 1222433 rows and 9 columns. There are 9 Variables, which include year, month, day, prcp (precipitation (mm)), snow (snowfall (mm)), snwd (snow depth (mm)), tmax (maximum temperature (degrees Celcius)), and tmin (minimum temperature (degrees Celcius)). The original dataset contains 2595176 observations, and 1372743 , Observations with missing data were removed from the original dataset.

  1. Make a two-panel plot showing (i) tmax vs tmin for the full dataset (note that a scatterplot may not be the best option); and (ii) make a plot showing the distribution of snowfall values greater than 0 and less than 100 separately by year.
t_maxmin_p = 
  nycweather_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = tmin, y = tmax)) +
  geom_bin2d() +
  labs(
    title = "tmax vs tmin",
    caption = "Data retrieved from the ny_noaa dataset from all  monitoning stations in NY, during January 1, 1981 through December 31, 2010."
  )
ggsave("t_maxmin_plot.pdf", t_maxmin_p, width = 8, height = 5)

snowfall_p = 
  nycweather_df %>%
  filter(snow > 0 & snow < 100) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = snow)) +
  geom_boxplot() +  
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1)) +
  labs(
  title = "Snowfall Distribution",
  caption = "Data from the ny_noaa dataset from all  monitoning stations in NY, during January 1, 1981 through December 31, 2010."
  )
ggsave("snowfall.pdf", snowfall_p, width = 8, height = 5)
